Amend the European Stability Pact
The European Stability Pact, which underpins the euro by establishing constraints determining the size of the budget deficits of Union members, is in danger.
Germany, the heavyweight of the Union, has not succeeded in meeting its budget commitments to its European partners.
Furthermore, it used its political weight to cover up the warning signal of its deficit, set up by the European Commission in accordance with the terms of the European Stability Pact.
Today it's France that's playing the bad boys.
The number 2 of the Union, not very enthusiastic, is now officially declaring that it cannot keep its commitment to reduce the budget deficit, a year after small Ireland received an official warning about its fiscal policies, despite its budget surpluses, and in a very severe way.
Thus, four years after its signature, the stability pact is a real disaster.
In fact, Europe seems to be very affected by the discussions aiming to eliminate it, as well as the discussions aiming to amend it.
And rightly so: the pact is poorly designed and its implementation was poorly done.
The limitation of the deficit to 3% of GDP is arbitrary and does not take into account the fact that deficits automatically increase when the economy slows down.
Assuming this fact, the architects of the pact have worsened the situation by adopting two thoughtless solutions.
They introduced a security clause allowing any country to suspend its deficit limits in case of significant recession, but they defined it in such a way that any suspension is almost impossible in practice.
Concerned that serious slowdowns could breach the deficit ceiling, they decreed that a normal deficit equaled zero deficit.
Thus, every year, each country must submit a budget projection for the two years ahead, demonstrating how the budget balance will be achieved on time.
The German commitment for 2002 was made in 2001, when its economy was growing at a reasonable rate.
The unexpected slowdown prevents Germany from achieving its goals.
The finance minister, Hans Eichel, reasonably decided not to exacerbate the situation by adopting a fiscal contraction policy.
The Commission, seeking to project itself as the protector of the pact, wanted to issue a warning, but this decision had to be taken by real politicians, the Council of Finance Ministers.
No one wanted to embarrass Germany since everyone recognized that they could be faced with the same problem in the future.
Thus, no warning was issued.
The situation in France is different.
In the election period, politicians inevitably make promises, particularly on reducing the tax burden.
In a country where the tax burden is significant, it's not just a matter of showing political intelligence, it's also a matter of showing economic intelligence, as long as budgetary expenses are also reduced.
However, France is also a country where everyone benefits from certain privileges financed by the state, and as a result, budget cuts are definitely poorly received.
Thus, France cannot meet its objectives, and the Commission has expressed its frustration.
But France has mastered the art of defying the laws of the Union.
Political maneuvers will follow, inevitably.
Economists and cynics are hardly surprised.
The objective of the pact, to put in place a fiscal discipline within countries sharing the same currency, is quite acceptable.
However, the loss of control over their national monetary policy, Union members now benefit from only one macroeconomic tool: fiscal policies.
The challenge is therefore to combine a long-term discipline with short-term flexibility.
Just like promising to go on a diet before a big party, this challenge is not easy to reconcile.
The stability pact is too primitive and technocratic: the 3% objective set by the Brussels bureaucrats cannot link politicians together.
The solution must be found elsewhere.
Luckily, we don't have to look too far.
The monetary policy faces the same challenge.
It must stabilize prices in the long term while remaining sufficiently flexible in the short term to manage economic cycles.
Over the past ten years, monetary policy has had a real success.
The recipe is the same everywhere: it's just a matter of delegating this policy to a competent group, the Central Bank, by giving it the necessary political independence and a clear and well-defined mandate.
Knowing that any blunder will have to be resolved in the future, it's up to them to show good sense.
This has proven to be one of the major improvements in the monetary field in recent years.
The same approach should work for fiscal policy.
Certainly, however, some fear losing democracy in it.
It is essential to understand that fiscal policy serves two very different purposes.
The first is structural and redistributive and concerns the importance of the budget and its detailed structure, both in terms of expenditure as well as in terms of revenue.
The decisions about these issues cannot be delegated and must remain in the hands of elected governments and be subject to parliamentary approval and management.
The second is macroeconomic: it is a matter of defining the budget balance to manage the fluctuations cycles.
It differs little from monetary policy and can be delegated to an independent body.
So, Europe's task is clear.
Each country must regain total control of its fiscal policies but delegate its macroeconomic components, its decisions on deficits or surpluses, to an independent fiscal policy Committee whose long-term objective is the stabilization (or reduction, for some countries) of public debt.
Pour en garantir le résultat, the outcome must be assured, the status of such a Committee and its mandates must be subject to a consensus within the Union, without any interference from Brussels, without any arbitrary regulation, without any political decision-making, but simply relying on common sense.
